'''Florence Marly''' (2 June 1919 – 9 November 1978) was a Czech-born French film actress.<ref name="PhillipsVincendeau2006">{{cite book|last1=Phillips|first1=Alastair|last2=Vincendeau|first2=Ginette|authorlink2=Ginette Vincendeau|title=Journeys of desire: European actors in Hollywood : a critical companion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xetkAAAAMAAJ|date=17 July 2006|publisher=BFI|isbn=978-1-84457-123-9|page=351}}</ref> During World War II, Marly moved to neutral Argentina with her Jewish husband, film director [[Pierre Chenal]], where she appeared in several films. She also acted in two of her husband's films while they were in Chile.<ref name="Plazaola1989">{{cite book|last=Plazaola|first=Luis Trelles|title=South American Cinema/ Cine De America Del Sur: Dictionary of Film Makers/ Diccionario De Los Productores De Peliculas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VansCHXxnZYC&pg=PA55|date=1 January 1989|publisher=La Editorial, UPR|isbn=978-0-8477-2011-8|page=55}}</ref>

==Career==
She played a major role in [[René Clément]]'s ''[[The Damned (1947 film)|Les Maudits]]'', a fictionalized account showing the fate of Nazi refugees.<ref name="KlinowskiGarbicz2012">{{cite book|last1=Klinowski|first1=Jacek|last2=Garbicz|first2=Adam|title=Feature Cinema in the 20th Century: Volume One: 1913-1950: a Comprehensive Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lpp93FevM2cC&pg=RA2-PT238|volume=1|year=2012|publisher=Planet RGB Limited|isbn=978-1-62407-564-3|page=238}}</ref> After moving to [[Hollywood]], she acted in Paramount's ''[[Sealed Verdict]]'' opposite [[Ray Milland]].<ref name="International1949">{{cite book|title=Sealed Verdict|journal=The Rotarian|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZEYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA53|date=January 1949|publisher=Rotary International|volume=74|issue=1|page=53|issn=0035-838X}}</ref> Next year, she starred in [[Stuart Heisler]]'s ''[[Tokyo Joe (1949 film)|Tokyo Joe]]'' (1949) alongside [[Humphrey Bogart]]. In it she played Bogart's wife, whom he divorces after she moves to the US from Japan during World War II. The film met with mixed responses from critics. [[Clive Hirschhorn]] wrote in his book, ''The Columbia Story'', that it was "a little more than a Bogart parody".<ref name="Blottner2015">{{cite book|last=Blottner|first=Gene|title=Columbia Noir: A Complete Filmography, 1940-1962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l9B7BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA231|date=17 March 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-1761-9|pages=230–231}}</ref> Marly's acting in the espionage film ''[[Tokyo File 212]]'' brought her appreciations. Robert J. Lentz wrote in ''Korean War Filmography'' that she had given the best performance in the film.<ref name="Lentz2003">{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Lentz|first=Robert J.|title=[[Korean War Filmography]]|year=2003|location=[[Jefferson, North Carolina]]|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=978-0-7864-1046-0|page=377|oclc=50630520}}</ref> It was Hollywood's first [[feature film]] to be shot entirely in Japan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tokyo File 212|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=50894|accessdate=16 April 2015|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]}}</ref>

In 1962 she appeared in a small role as a gangster's girlfriend in the [[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|Twilight Zone]] episode [[Dead Man's Shoes (The Twilight Zone)|''Dead Man's Shoes'']].<ref name="Lofficier2003">{{cite book|last1=Lofficier|first1=Jean-Marc|last2= Lofficier|first2=Randy|title=Into The Twilight Zone: The Rod Serling Programme Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2pNRBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT44|date=15 April 2003|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=978-1-4620-9900-9|page=44}}</ref> She had the eponymous role of a blood-thirsty vampire queen in [[Curtis Harrington]]-directed science fiction horror film ''[[Queen of Blood]]'' (1966), based on a novel by Charles Nuetzel.<ref name="Painter2010">{{cite book|last=Painter|first=Deborah|title=Forry: The Life of Forrest J Ackerman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sL2oreiBQ6wC&pg=PA75|date=15 November 2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5798-4|page=75}}</ref> It met with positive reviews.<ref name="Shelley2009">{{cite book|last=Shelley|first=Peter|authorlink=Peter Shelley|title=Grande Dame Guignol Cinema: A History of Hag Horror from Baby Jane to Mother|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gPuyHmIcHbwC&pg=PA97|date=15 September 2009|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5485-3|page=97}}</ref> Paul Meehan wrote in ''Saucer Movies'' that she gave a "convincing" performance.<ref name="Meehan1998">{{cite book|last=Meehan|first=Paul|title=Saucer Movies: A UFOlogical History of the Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vHlZAAAAMAAJ|date=1 January 1998|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-3573-3|page=125}}</ref> Marly made a [[16 mm]] sequel to ''Queen of Blood'' titled ''Space Boy!'' (1973).<ref name="Space">{{cite book|title=Video Watchdog|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2YuGAAAAIAAJ|year=1993|publisher=Tim & Donna Lucas|page=80|issue=15-20}}</ref>

==Personal life==
At a dinner, director [[Fritz Lang]] bit Marly's hand.<ref name="Painter2010" /> During the early years of her acting career, the U.S. Consulate mistook her for the Russian-born, left-inclined, singer and songwriter [[Anna Marly]], and she was subsequently blacklisted in Hollywood by the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]].<!--the "blacklist" was by the movie industry, influenced by HUAC (needs citation)--> Even after she was cleared from the blacklist, at a Hollywood party [[Jack L. Warner]] "turned his back on [her]".<ref name="Malone2015">{{cite book|last=Malone|first=Aubrey|title=Hollywood's Second Sex: The Treatment of Women in the Film Industry, 1900-1999|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ubQGCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA156|date=10 April 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-1951-4|page=156}}</ref> [[Noël Coward]], in a letter, called her a "rather sweet" "beautiful Czech lady".<ref name="Coward2014">{{cite book|last=Coward|first=Noël|authorlink=Noël Coward|title=The Letters of Noël Coward|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6FOBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT596|date=31 October 2014|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4081-4767-2|page=596}}</ref> She was married to Chenal from 1937 to 1955.<ref name="Rège2009">{{cite book|last=Rège|first=Philippe|title=Encyclopedia of French Film Directors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ud2-AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA211|volume=1|date=11 December 2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6939-4|page=211}}</ref> In 1956 she married the Austrian Count Degenhart von Wurmbrand-Stuppach (1893-1965) but divorced the same year.

